         <abstract>
            <p>The CAPM is embroiled in controversy regarding whether it is empirically valid or not. The best way to save the fundamental concept of diversification from being damaged by the CAPM's weak credibility is to expand our treatment of the individual investor's portfolio optimization problem. We need to teach that diversification is always a useful investment strategy and does not depend on whether the CAPM is true or not. The primary obstacle to doing this is the matrix algebra required by mean-variance analysis. I offer a new approach using an Excel-based interactive optimizer. I provide it free on the Web:www.bus.indiana.edu/finweb/holden.htm</p>
         </abstract>
